> We've fallen in love with dukkah—an Egyptian spice blend containing crushed nuts, sesame
> seeds, cumin, and coriander. It's earthy and nutty in all the best ways. It gives this
> simple, pan-seared chicken and roasted sweet potatoes a major upgrade!

Preheat the #oven{} to 400 degrees. Trim the @Sugar Snap Peas{12%ounce}. Cut the
@Sweet Potatoes{24%ounce} into ½-inch cubes. Toss them on a #baking sheet{} with half the
@Dukkah{1%tablespoon}, a large drizzle of @Olive Oil{2%box}, and a pinch of @Salt{pinch}
and @Pepper{pinch}. Place in the oven, tossing halfway through cooking, for approximately
~{25%minutes}, until golden brown.

Zest, then halve the @Lime{2}(zested and halved). In a #small bowl{}, mix the
@Sour Cream{8%ounce}, a pinch of lime zest, and a squeeze of lime juice. Season to taste
with salt and pepper. Thin to a drizzling consistency using a teaspoon or so of @Water{}.

Place your hand on top of the @Chicken Breasts{24%ounce} and slice into the center of the
meat, parallel to the #cutting board{}. Stop before cutting all the way through. Open
the chicken up like a book, cover with #plastic wrap{}, and pound with a #mallet{} or
large pan until ½-inch thick. Repeat with the other chicken breast. Season on all sides
with salt, pepper, and the remaining @Dukkah{1%tablespoon}.

Cook the chicken: Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat.
Once hot, add the chicken to the pan and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} per side, until cooked
through. Remove from the pan and set aside to rest.

Cook the snap peas: Heat another drizzle of oil in the same pan over medium heat. Add the
snap peas and cook, tossing for ~{4-5%minutes}, until crisp-tender. Season with salt and
pepper.

Finish and plate: Serve the chicken on a bed of roasted sweet potatoes and snap peas.
Drizzle with the citrus sour cream and enjoy.